  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_0' aria-label=\" Neha Enterprises versus Commissioner, Commercial Tax, Lucknow, Uttar Pradesh pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('0','2025','2025_5_475_484','2025INSC476'); ><font size='4'> <strong>NEHA ENTERPRISES<span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>COMMISSIONER, COMMERCIAL TAX, LUCKNOW, UTTAR PRADESH </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 5 S.C.R. 475</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 476</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010001732025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : PANKAJ MITHAL<sup style=\"color: #268e97;font-size: 22px;top: 0;\" class=\"tooltip-sup\" data-tooltip=\"Author\">*</sup>, SARASA VENKATANARAYANA BHATTI</strong><br> Issue for Consideration Matter pertains to disallowance of the input tax credit claimed by the dealer. Whether the assessing officer correctly held that the dealer is not entitled to input tax credit for the purchase tax paid by him on the sales turnover made in favour of Value Added Tax Act, 2008 &ndash; s.7(c) and s.13(7) &ndash; The appellant-dealer claimed an input tax credit amounting to Rs. 6,42,260/- &ndash; The assessing officer, at the first instance, allowed input tax to the extent of Rs. 6,42,260/- &ndash; Subsequently, the assessing officer vide order<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 08-04-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CIVIL APPEAL No. 6553/2016</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Dismissed</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('0','2025','2025_5_475_484','2025INSC476','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>S